<paragraph id="8B8536EB5B725006FF2FFAD737A35813" blockId="3.[148,978,1231,1570]" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">
The 
<typeStatus id="548188495B725006FF5EFAD737045B58" box="[221,308,1364,1385]" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">lectotype</typeStatus>
(SBL 
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FEFDFAD737A05B59" bold="true" box="[382,400,1364,1384]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">¼</emphasis>
<quantity id="4CC29B0E5B725006FE18FAD737CA5B58" box="[411,506,1364,1385]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1199999999999999" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" unit="mm" value="11.2">11.2 mm</quantity>
; ABL 
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FDC7FAD734665B59" bold="true" box="[580,598,1364,1384]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">¼</emphasis>
about 
<quantity id="4CC29B0E5B725006FD20FAD734CF5B58" box="[675,767,1364,1385]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" unit="mm" value="13.5">13.5 mm</quantity>
) is conspecific with specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D685B725006FE96FAED34705BB2" authority="(Chaudoir, 1843)" baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[277,576,1390,1411]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FE96FAED37A65BB2" box="[277,406,1390,1411]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
(Chaudoir, 1843)
</taxonomicName>
[NEW SYNONYMY]. As pointed out by Allen (1972:128), 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D685B725006FE8FFA0A37A05BAF" baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[268,400,1417,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FE8FFA0A37A05BAF" box="[268,400,1417,1438]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘‘is very distinct.’’ It is the largest species of the genus in North America, though large specimens of a few species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D685B725006FC86FA20350F5B89" box="[773,831,1443,1464]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectus">
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FC86FA20350F5B89" box="[773,831,1443,1464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">rectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FCF2FA2035E15B89" box="[881,977,1443,1464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">erracticus</emphasis>
groups could reach the size range of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D685B725006FE6DFA3D345F5BE2" baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[494,623,1470,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis id="B94EEAF95B725006FE6DFA3D345F5BE2" box="[494,623,1470,1491]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a very characteristic pronotum: the sides are evenly rounded, the posterior angles widely rounded, the lateral margins explanate at base in most specimens, the lateral beads indistinct, and the anterior sulcus is not impressed medially.
</paragraph>
